<section xml:id="section-cartesian-coordinates">

    <title>Cartesian Coordinates</title>

    <p>When we model real-life data with graphs, we use the <term>Cartesian coordinate system</term>. This section covers the basic vocabulary and ideas that come with the Cartesian coordinate system.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="N4nrdf0yYfM" />
    </figure>

    <p>The Cartesian coordinate system is just a way to identify <em>where</em> points are on a flat area. It's basically an address, so we will start with an example that uses a street grid. Here is a street map with Carl's home at the center, covering some nearby businesses. Assume each unit represents one city block.</p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-carls-neighborhood">
        <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
        <image width="60%">
            <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
            <latex-image-code>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                            xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                            ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                            xtick={-4,4},
                            ytick={-4,4},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[pin=-30:{restaurant}] {};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[pin=100:{pet shop}] {};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, -4)} node[pin=150:{gas station}] {};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[pin=120:{bar}] {};
                    \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                    \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                    \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                    \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>If Carl has an out-of-town guest who asks him how to get to the restaurant, one way to give directions is:</p>
    <blockquote><p><q>Go <m>2</m> blocks east, and then <m>3</m> blocks north.</q></p></blockquote>

    <sidebyside>
        <p>So two numbers are needed to locate the restaurant. In a Cartesian coordinate system, we write these numbers this way: <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the restaurant's location. Note that the first number, <m>2</m>, represents the location in the east-west direction, and the second number, <m>3</m>, represents the location in north-south direction.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
            <image>
                <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                                xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                xtick={-4,4},
                                ytick={-4,4},
                                clip=false]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[pin=-30:{restaurant}] {} node[left] {$(2,3)$};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (2,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {right $2$};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,->] coordinates {(2,0) (2,2.8)} node[below,pos=0.5,rotate=90] {up $3$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>To travel from Carl's home to the pet shop, he would go <m>3</m> blocks west, and then <m>2</m> blocks north.</p>

    <sidebyside>
        <p>We think of rightward and upward as <em>positive</em> directions, and leftward and downward as <em>negative</em> directions. So we use positive numbers to represent the east, and negative numbers to represent the west. The pet shop's location would be <m>(-3,2)</m> in a Cartesian coordinate system.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
            <image>
                <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                                xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                xtick={-4,4},
                                ytick={-4,4},
                                clip=false]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[pin=100:{pet shop}] {} node[above right] {$(-3,2)$};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (-3,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {left $3$};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,->] coordinates {(-3,0) (-3,1.8)} node[below,pos=0.5,rotate=90] {up $2$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

    </sidebyside>

    <remark>
        <p>It's important to not mix up which coordinate comes first. Since we read from left to right, the left-right coordinate is the first number in the ordered pair. This idea of putting the horizontal information <em>before</em> the vertical information is consistent through most of mathematics.</p>
    </remark>

    <aside>
        <title>Coordinates <abbr>vs.</abbr> Intervals</title>
        <p>Unfortunately, the way we write ordered pairs looks exactly like the way we write open intervals in interval notation. It's up to you to use <em>context</em> to understand if something like <m>(2,3)</m> is the point <m>2</m> units right of the origin and <m>3</m> units up, or the interval of all numbers between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p>
    </aside>

