    <p>In a Cartesian coordinate system, the map of Carl's neighborhood would look like this:</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Carl's Neighborhood in a Cartesian Coordinate System</caption>
        <image width="50%">
            <description>a Cartesian grid points <m>(0,0), (2, 3), (-3,2), (-2,-4),</m> and <m>(3, -3)</m>, with <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis labeled</description>
            <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                xtick={-4,4},
                                ytick={-4,4}]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[above right] {(0,0)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[above] {(2,3)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[above] {(-3,2)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, -4)} node[above] {(-2,-4)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[above] {(3,-3)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image-code>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>It's traditional to use the variable <m>x</m> to represent numbers on the east-west axis, so we call that axis the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>. For similar reasons we call the north-south axis the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>. The point <m>(0,0)</m> is where the two axes meet, and we call it the <term>origin</term>. <index><main>origin</main></index> We use an <term>ordered pair</term>, like <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the location of a point. We are ready for a formal definition of the <term>Cartesian Coordinate System</term> and several associated vocabulary terms.</p>


    <definition>
        <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
        <index><main>Cartesian</main><sub>Coordinate System</sub></index>
        <statement>
            <p>A Cartesian coordinate system is a coordinate system that specifies each point uniquely in a plane by a pair of numerical coordinates, which are the signed (positive/negative) distances to the point from two fixed perpendicular directed lines, measured in the same unit of length. Those two reference lines are called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term> and <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>, and the point where they meet is its <term>origin</term>, the <term>ordered pair</term> <m>(0, 0)</m>. (Visit <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system">Wikipedia</url> for more.)</p>

            <p>The plane based on the <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis is called a <term>coordinate plane</term>. The ordered pair used to locate a point is called the point's <term>coordinates</term>, which consists of an <term><m>x</m>-coordinate</term> and a <term><m>y</m>-coordinate</term>. For example, for the point <m>(1,2)\text{,}</m> its <m>x</m>-coordinate is <m>1\text{,}</m> and its <m>y</m>-coordinate is <m>2\text{.}</m></p>

            <p>A Cartesian coordinate system is divided into four <term>quadrants</term>, as shown in <xref ref="figure-quadrants">Figure</xref>. The quadrants are traditionally labeled with Roman numerals.</p>

            <figure xml:id="figure-quadrants">
                <caption>A Cartesian grid with four quardrants marked</caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with Quardrant I marked in the top right section, Quardrant II marked in the top left section, Quardrant III marked in the bottom left section, Quardrant IV marked in the bottom right section.</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},
                                    ytick={-4,-3,...,4}]
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3,3)} node[below] {Quardrant I};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3, 3)} node[below] {Quardrant II};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3, -3)} node[above] {Quardrant III};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[above] {Quardrant IV};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
    </definition>


    <example xml:id="example-cartesian-points">
        <statement>
            <p>On paper, sketch a Cartesian coordinate system with units, and then plot the following points: <m>(3,2),(-5,-1),(0,-3),(4,0)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <!--<todo>Make this a sidebyside, with a video right next to the tikz picture. The video will be an overhead of someone doing this by hand on real paper.</todo>-->
        <solution>
            <figure>
                <caption>Solution to <xref ref="example-cartesian-points">Example</xref></caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <description>a Cartesian grid points <m>(3,2),(-2,-1),(0,-3),(4,0)</m> plotted</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},
                                    ytick={-4,-3,...,4}]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 2)} node[above] {$(3,2)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, -1)} node[below] {$(-2,-1)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, -3)} node[right] {$(0,-3)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4, 0)} node[above] {$(4,0)$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

